---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Why Old Songs Still Make Money | Artist Money"
  description="Why evergreen songs stay commercially alive decades after release."
  type="article"
>
  <section>
    <p class="eyebrow">Explainer</p>
    <h1>Why old songs still make money</h1>
    <p>
      Evergreen songs survive because they stay useful. They fit playlists, trigger nostalgia,
      support sync use, and remain legible to new listeners long after their release cycle is over.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Main drivers</h2>
    <ul class="meta-list">
      <li>Editorial and algorithmic playlists keep classic tracks in circulation.</li>
      <li>Nostalgia creates repeat listening across multiple generations.</li>
      <li>Film, TV, trailers, and internet culture repeatedly reintroduce older songs.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Why it matters for artists</h2>
    <p>
      Music is one of the few creative assets that can keep generating income for decades. That is
      why catalog ownership, licensing rights, and long-tail relevance matter so much.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
